There are many smart and creative kids who wanted to pursue an artistic career, who were also too pragmatic and responsible to take the jump because their family struggled financially;

and by the time they reached a bit of financial security, they no longer enjoyed books, music, art like they used to, and that's a very tragic sight, because you can never be the most joyful, happy, alive version of yourself as long as you forgot about who you were meant to be;

that's how you end up with so many adults who may have covered their materialistic needs, but who also seem emotionally absent, disconnected from who they forgot they wanted to be: present, playful, creative; they have money without wealth, games without fun, goals without purpose.
